1
00:00:07,757 --> 00:00:10,593
Abrasions on the hand…

2
00:00:10,677 --> 00:00:13,638
…rib fracture… from CPR…

3
00:00:14,472 --> 00:00:16,099
Darn! This will never end.

4
00:00:16,182 --> 00:00:17,267
You scared me.

5
00:00:17,350 --> 00:00:19,436
Too many reports. Someone take over.

6
00:00:19,519 --> 00:00:20,979
I'm busy organizing files.

7
00:00:21,062 --> 00:00:22,522
Same, I got inspection reports.

8
00:00:22,605 --> 00:00:23,565
I can't either.

9
00:00:26,818 --> 00:00:29,654
The MEJ is different from what I imagined.

10
00:00:29,738 --> 00:00:30,739
Tell me about it.

11
00:00:30,822 --> 00:00:34,117
Makes me want to go back
to university research labs ASAP.

12
00:00:35,076 --> 00:00:36,369
Dr. Honda, you're finished?

13
00:00:36,453 --> 00:00:38,705
- With ease.
- I still have some, if you're free.

14
00:00:38,788 --> 00:00:39,873
I have plans tonight.

15
00:00:39,956 --> 00:00:40,999
Oh, a date.

16
00:00:41,082 --> 00:00:42,000
No.

17
00:00:42,083 --> 00:00:44,127
Going for drinks with an old colleague.

18
00:00:44,210 --> 00:00:45,253
Lucky.

19
00:00:45,336 --> 00:00:46,713
See you later.

20
00:00:49,382 --> 00:00:51,634
Shall we get to it then?

21
00:00:53,136 --> 00:00:54,012
Okay.

22
00:00:55,889 --> 00:01:00,018
…the coronary artery tissue of…

23
00:01:01,061 --> 00:01:02,687
Dr. Matsubara.

24
00:01:03,188 --> 00:01:05,190
- Can you put yourself on mute?
- What?

25
00:01:06,608 --> 00:01:07,859
Sorry.

26
00:01:09,652 --> 00:01:10,612
Welcome.

27
00:01:10,695 --> 00:01:11,571
Hello.

28
00:01:14,657 --> 00:01:15,658
Hey!

29
00:01:16,117 --> 00:01:17,368
Hirono.

30
00:01:17,452 --> 00:01:18,703
Here's your <i>oden.</i>

31
00:01:18,787 --> 00:01:20,497
Hey, do you remember?

32
00:01:21,039 --> 00:01:23,416
That massive pile-up on the highway.

33
00:01:23,500 --> 00:01:25,418
Of course, I remember.

34
00:01:25,502 --> 00:01:27,587
That was brutal.

35
00:01:27,670 --> 00:01:29,589
We saw 30 patients in one night.

36
00:01:29,672 --> 00:01:31,382
Pretty much just the two of us.

37
00:01:31,466 --> 00:01:34,552
Once you've survived a scene like that,
nothing scares you anymore.

38
00:01:34,636 --> 00:01:35,637
True.

39
00:01:35,720 --> 00:01:39,432
And then, we had a toast
in that empty lobby afterward.

40
00:01:39,516 --> 00:01:42,852
That canned beer
was the best in the world at that moment.

41
00:01:43,436 --> 00:01:45,897
Spoken like a guy
who was drinking non-alcoholic.

42
00:01:47,690 --> 00:01:50,693
More importantly, how's the new workplace?

43
00:01:51,277 --> 00:01:52,570
MEJ, is it?

44
00:01:53,822 --> 00:01:54,739
Yes.

45
00:01:55,532 --> 00:01:56,533
It's the worst.

46
00:01:56,616 --> 00:01:57,700
Really?

47
00:01:57,784 --> 00:02:00,286
The police and everyone else
find us annoying.

48
00:02:00,870 --> 00:02:03,039
<i>I have no idea what my boss is thinking.</i>

49
00:02:03,123 --> 00:02:04,666
<i>He's a weirdo.</i>

50
00:02:05,250 --> 00:02:07,544
I'm worked to the bone for low pay, too.

51
00:02:07,627 --> 00:02:08,545
I see.

52
00:02:09,212 --> 00:02:10,797
You've got it good.

53
00:02:10,880 --> 00:02:13,591
Settled in nicely as a surgeon
at Meiwa University.

54
00:02:14,175 --> 00:02:16,594
I should never have gone
into forensic medicine.

55
00:02:20,640 --> 00:02:22,016
Honda, you know--

56
00:02:22,100 --> 00:02:25,103
Don't start with the comforting words.

57
00:02:39,784 --> 00:02:42,245
- Sorry, it's work.
- Top doctors have it tough.

58
00:02:42,328 --> 00:02:44,581
Sorry, it's work I really can't miss.

59
00:02:44,664 --> 00:02:45,498
Sure.

60
00:02:45,957 --> 00:02:47,709
I'll make it up to you next time.

61
00:02:50,920 --> 00:02:51,838
You know, I--

62
00:02:51,921 --> 00:02:53,131
Just go.

63
00:02:53,214 --> 00:02:54,173
You're busy, right?

64
00:02:57,176 --> 00:02:59,012
Let's talk properly next time.

65
00:03:00,597 --> 00:03:02,181
Good luck.

66
00:03:09,606 --> 00:03:11,816
My head hurts.

67
00:03:11,900 --> 00:03:13,109
A hangover?

68
00:03:13,192 --> 00:03:15,028
Coming into work after partying?

69
00:03:15,111 --> 00:03:16,446
That's just wrong.

70
00:03:16,529 --> 00:03:17,614
You stink.

71
00:03:17,697 --> 00:03:20,533
I went home after
my friend got called into work.

72
00:03:20,617 --> 00:03:22,327
- An emergency patient?
- Yes.

73
00:03:22,410 --> 00:03:24,537
He's a surgeon at Meiwa University.

74
00:03:24,621 --> 00:03:26,998
He's moving up in the world. Unlike you.

75
00:03:27,081 --> 00:03:30,418
Dr. Honda, the toxicology report…

76
00:03:30,501 --> 00:03:32,086
I turned it in yesterday.

77
00:03:32,170 --> 00:03:35,715
There's an error in the diagnosis
of the poison, please fix it.

78
00:03:35,798 --> 00:03:38,801
No way, I was certain
everything was correct.

79
00:03:38,885 --> 00:03:42,597
No, the lethal dose of Olanzapine
was overlooked.

80
00:03:43,306 --> 00:03:44,265
Oh.

81
00:03:46,643 --> 00:03:48,228
This is Medical Examiner Japan.

82
00:03:48,311 --> 00:03:51,481
Someone please also
cross-reference it with past cases?

83
00:03:52,357 --> 00:03:53,524
Okay.

84
00:03:53,608 --> 00:03:56,277
There's so much to do
even without any autopsies.

85
00:03:56,361 --> 00:03:57,987
I wish we got paid extra.

86
00:03:59,781 --> 00:04:00,990
Yes.

87
00:04:03,034 --> 00:04:05,119
Yes, goodbye.

88
00:04:09,332 --> 00:04:10,500
Dr. Honda.

89
00:04:10,583 --> 00:04:11,668
Yeah?

90
00:04:12,502 --> 00:04:13,962
Where did your friend work?

91
00:04:14,587 --> 00:04:15,922
Meiwa University Hospital?

92
00:04:16,005 --> 00:04:17,382
What was that call?

93
00:04:18,716 --> 00:04:21,511
There's a body of a person
who died an unnatural death.

94
00:04:23,388 --> 00:04:24,347
What?

95
00:04:38,903 --> 00:04:40,280
This can't be real.

96
00:04:41,698 --> 00:04:43,283
He knows the victim?

97
00:04:44,158 --> 00:04:45,618
It seems he was his friend.

98
00:04:45,702 --> 00:04:47,870
They went drinking together last night.

99
00:04:47,954 --> 00:04:51,124
Ms. Dojima! We haven't been able
to find his smartphone.

100
00:04:51,207 --> 00:04:53,084
There are no surveillance cameras nearby.

101
00:04:53,167 --> 00:04:54,961
We don't know what happened.

102
00:04:57,422 --> 00:04:58,464
The cause of death

103
00:04:58,548 --> 00:05:01,009
was a cerebral contusion
from a strong blow to the head.

104
00:05:01,092 --> 00:05:05,555
Or perhaps internal organ damage
from multiple fractures.

105
00:05:05,638 --> 00:05:08,933
This is a condition seen
when there is a violent collision.

106
00:05:09,017 --> 00:05:10,435
Like a traffic accident?

107
00:05:10,518 --> 00:05:13,146
In that case,
there would usually be secondary injuries

108
00:05:13,229 --> 00:05:16,232
from being thrown onto the hood
or windshield,

109
00:05:16,316 --> 00:05:19,652
and tertiary ones
from hitting the road's surface.

110
00:05:20,278 --> 00:05:21,154
It doesn't add up.

111
00:05:21,237 --> 00:05:22,322
It doesn't add up.

112
00:05:22,405 --> 00:05:23,364
It doesn't add up.

113
00:05:23,448 --> 00:05:24,615
Rather than that,

114
00:05:25,199 --> 00:05:29,412
it looks as though he fell
from several meters above.

115
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:36,210
Are you saying he fell from the sky?

116
00:05:36,294 --> 00:05:38,755
An example, going by the evidence I see.

117
00:05:38,838 --> 00:05:41,132
- Supervisor.
- Yes?

118
00:05:41,841 --> 00:05:45,428
Maybe the crime scene was elsewhere,
and he was moved here? Or something?

119
00:05:45,511 --> 00:05:48,473
There are blood droplets
directly beneath the body.

120
00:05:48,556 --> 00:05:49,974
It doesn't add up.

121
00:05:50,058 --> 00:05:51,350
In any case,

122
00:05:51,434 --> 00:05:54,854
he must have fallen somewhere
not too far from here.

123
00:05:54,937 --> 00:05:58,232
Well, even if you say it's not too far…

124
00:05:58,983 --> 00:06:00,818
- He really fell from the sky?
- Idiot!

125
00:06:00,902 --> 00:06:04,238
Don't say stupid stuff, it's annoying.

126
00:06:04,322 --> 00:06:05,323
Sorry.

127
00:06:05,406 --> 00:06:07,158
These bloodstains…

128
00:06:10,078 --> 00:06:11,454
What is it?

129
00:06:12,288 --> 00:06:14,791
Possibly from when he fell,

130
00:06:14,874 --> 00:06:19,045
but in that case
the amount of blood is far too small.

131
00:06:24,050 --> 00:06:25,551
It doesn't add up.

132
00:06:27,011 --> 00:06:29,097
Could we ask you a few questions?

133
00:06:31,390 --> 00:06:32,642
Sure.

134
00:06:32,725 --> 00:06:35,645
Okay. First, what was your relationship
with the victim?

135
00:06:36,938 --> 00:06:40,316
We were colleagues when we worked
as ER doctors.

136
00:06:41,734 --> 00:06:43,736
And you were with him last night?

137
00:06:43,820 --> 00:06:45,238
We had dinner.

138
00:06:45,321 --> 00:06:46,739
What time?

139
00:06:47,448 --> 00:06:48,699
Dr. Honda.

140
00:06:50,409 --> 00:06:52,954
You don't have to do the autopsy.
You can take--

141
00:06:53,037 --> 00:06:54,122
Bureaucrats

142
00:06:55,081 --> 00:06:56,457
are soft, aren't they?

143
00:07:38,374 --> 00:07:39,667
Let's begin.

144
00:08:00,855 --> 00:08:04,817
As a result of the autopsy,
the direct cause of death was indeed

145
00:08:04,901 --> 00:08:07,987
a cerebral contusion from a strong
impact to the back of the head.

146
00:08:08,070 --> 00:08:09,322
However, before that,

147
00:08:09,405 --> 00:08:11,616
Mr. Hirono took a heavy blow
to his lower back.

148
00:08:11,699 --> 00:08:14,660
<i>I believe there is no doubt</i>
<i>that he fell from a height</i>

149
00:08:14,744 --> 00:08:17,788
<i>of about ten meters, landing on his back.</i>

150
00:08:19,040 --> 00:08:22,710
At the moment, we have no reports
of people falling out of airplanes.

151
00:08:22,793 --> 00:08:23,711
Of course not.

152
00:08:23,794 --> 00:08:27,507
Furthermore, there were abrasions
on his right arm and left leg,

153
00:08:27,590 --> 00:08:30,176
as if something had rubbed
against the skin.

154
00:08:30,259 --> 00:08:31,594
They look like burns.

155
00:08:31,677 --> 00:08:34,514
I wonder. Doesn't look like
the skin is peeling either.

156
00:08:34,597 --> 00:08:36,516
What do you mean, they look like burns?

157
00:08:37,141 --> 00:08:38,726
So he did not actually fall?

158
00:08:38,809 --> 00:08:42,855
These injuries were not fatal,
and no doubt it was a death from falling.

159
00:08:46,025 --> 00:08:48,319
Something bothering me is

160
00:08:49,779 --> 00:08:51,906
that there is absolutely
no gas in his intestines.

161
00:08:51,989 --> 00:08:53,991
His rectus abdominis muscle
is expanded out.

162
00:08:54,075 --> 00:08:56,536
Temporary post-mortem expansion?

163
00:08:57,328 --> 00:08:58,246
Probably.

164
00:08:58,329 --> 00:08:59,747
Expansion?

165
00:08:59,830 --> 00:09:01,707
Is there a connection to the fall?

166
00:09:01,791 --> 00:09:03,584
That is also unknown.

167
00:09:03,668 --> 00:09:04,627
Also,

168
00:09:04,710 --> 00:09:07,922
in the back of his throat,
his lungs, and his hair

169
00:09:08,005 --> 00:09:11,175
a small amount
of a powdery substance was found.

170
00:09:11,759 --> 00:09:14,679
<i>Detailed tests</i>
<i>are currently being carried out.</i>

171
00:09:15,596 --> 00:09:18,182
So in the end, we don't know anything.

172
00:09:18,266 --> 00:09:19,100
That's right.

173
00:09:19,976 --> 00:09:21,227
Not at this point.

174
00:09:21,310 --> 00:09:24,397
Contact me if you find out anything.

175
00:09:24,480 --> 00:09:25,398
Okay.

176
00:09:25,481 --> 00:09:27,275
Same to you, Ms. Dojima.

177
00:09:27,358 --> 00:09:30,945
I will if we find a witness who saw
a guy flying in the sky.

178
00:09:37,034 --> 00:09:38,244
It's ridiculous.

179
00:09:38,327 --> 00:09:39,829
First, we'll do questioning.

180
00:09:39,912 --> 00:09:40,746
Yes, ma'am!

181
00:09:40,830 --> 00:09:42,790
Could this powder-like stuff

182
00:09:43,541 --> 00:09:46,210
be wood dust from these trees?

183
00:09:46,294 --> 00:09:48,045
He climbed a tree and fell?

184
00:09:48,129 --> 00:09:50,673
Could be, if we found
alcohol intoxication.

185
00:09:50,756 --> 00:09:51,716
Then,

186
00:09:52,508 --> 00:09:54,302
from the roof of this stadium?

187
00:09:54,385 --> 00:09:57,346
But the distance from where he was found
is eight meters.

188
00:09:57,430 --> 00:09:59,473
If he fell from there…

189
00:10:01,392 --> 00:10:03,185
He would have to do a long jump.

190
00:10:04,145 --> 00:10:06,272
Did he even fall on his own?

191
00:10:06,355 --> 00:10:07,898
Maybe he was pushed?

192
00:10:07,982 --> 00:10:09,650
Someone with a grudge against him?

193
00:10:09,734 --> 00:10:11,235
That's not possible.

194
00:10:11,319 --> 00:10:12,236
What?

195
00:10:13,279 --> 00:10:16,907
There's no way someone
would hold a grudge against Hirono.

196
00:10:18,075 --> 00:10:19,410
Dr. Honda, let's go.

197
00:10:19,994 --> 00:10:23,748
Until the appraisal results are out,
I'm going to look into Hirono's work.

198
00:10:23,831 --> 00:10:24,915
At the hospital?

199
00:10:24,999 --> 00:10:28,628
Hirono cut the drinking session short,
saying he suddenly had work,

200
00:10:28,711 --> 00:10:30,004
and then died.

201
00:10:30,087 --> 00:10:32,757
He might have been meeting someone.

202
00:10:33,466 --> 00:10:34,925
Come on…

203
00:10:35,009 --> 00:10:37,470
When looking into
the victim's surroundings,

204
00:10:37,553 --> 00:10:40,931
it's convenient to have someone
who knew him well with me.

205
00:10:45,394 --> 00:10:47,980
I'd like to ask about
an incident at Miyagawa park…

206
00:10:48,064 --> 00:10:50,024
Thank you for your cooperation.

207
00:10:52,902 --> 00:10:53,819
Sir!

208
00:10:53,903 --> 00:10:56,322
Are you a resident of that apartment?

209
00:10:56,405 --> 00:10:57,281
Yes.

210
00:10:57,365 --> 00:10:59,492
Could I speak with you for a moment?

211
00:11:02,787 --> 00:11:04,121
A collision sound?

212
00:11:04,205 --> 00:11:05,831
There was a terrible noise.

213
00:11:06,540 --> 00:11:08,209
I rushed to open the window,

214
00:11:08,751 --> 00:11:10,419
but I couldn't see anything.

215
00:11:11,295 --> 00:11:13,672
Your daughter must have been startled too.

216
00:11:15,257 --> 00:11:16,217
Yes.

217
00:11:16,884 --> 00:11:19,887
I thought maybe
there had been an accident,

218
00:11:19,970 --> 00:11:22,973
but then I heard the sound
of a car driving away,

219
00:11:23,057 --> 00:11:24,725
so it was probably nothing.

220
00:11:26,018 --> 00:11:27,728
A car driving away…

221
00:11:29,438 --> 00:11:30,356
So good.

222
00:11:36,654 --> 00:11:39,115
We'll re-examine if there were
any suspicious vehicles.

223
00:11:39,198 --> 00:11:40,199
I'll re-examine.

224
00:11:40,282 --> 00:11:42,576
There's no way a human
would fall from the sky.

225
00:11:42,660 --> 00:11:43,828
No way at all.

226
00:11:44,620 --> 00:11:46,580
I've talked to the surgery department.

227
00:11:47,164 --> 00:11:48,416
Thank you.

228
00:11:48,499 --> 00:11:49,875
Just a moment.

229
00:11:49,959 --> 00:11:50,835
Okay.

230
00:11:54,839 --> 00:11:57,842
I really am glad
you came along, Dr. Honda.

231
00:11:59,802 --> 00:12:01,053
It's Hirono.

232
00:12:01,679 --> 00:12:03,431
I had to come.

233
00:12:06,851 --> 00:12:07,852
I…

234
00:12:09,311 --> 00:12:11,856
think I should just be doing autopsies.

235
00:12:11,939 --> 00:12:13,482
I am a forensic pathologist.

236
00:12:17,361 --> 00:12:20,156
What kind of person was Hirono?

237
00:12:21,031 --> 00:12:23,534
As a friend. It's just for reference.

238
00:12:25,870 --> 00:12:27,163
He was a good guy.

239
00:12:28,080 --> 00:12:29,165
Kind.

240
00:12:29,790 --> 00:12:30,958
Passionate.

241
00:12:33,502 --> 00:12:36,046
Not the kind of person
anyone would hold a grudge against.

242
00:12:36,881 --> 00:12:38,174
Definitely not.

243
00:12:41,594 --> 00:12:45,306
However, Hirono has passed away.

244
00:12:46,724 --> 00:12:52,813
Perhaps there were aspects of his life
that you didn't know about, Dr. Honda.

245
00:12:52,897 --> 00:12:54,273
Don't you think?

246
00:12:57,485 --> 00:12:59,069
Sorry to keep you waiting.

247
00:12:59,153 --> 00:13:00,279
Thank you.

248
00:13:10,915 --> 00:13:13,250
He was still so young, it's such a shame.

249
00:13:13,334 --> 00:13:16,295
What kind of person was Dr. Hirono?

250
00:13:16,378 --> 00:13:17,588
Who knows?

251
00:13:17,671 --> 00:13:19,840
We never talked about personal things.

252
00:13:19,924 --> 00:13:21,800
I only remember scolding him.

253
00:13:22,593 --> 00:13:23,469
What?

254
00:13:25,221 --> 00:13:28,516
You were his supervising doctor,
right, Dr. Imabayashi?

255
00:13:28,599 --> 00:13:32,520
Back when he was an intern.
He did nothing but make mistakes.

256
00:13:33,103 --> 00:13:36,190
I don't want to speak ill of him,
now that he's no more.

257
00:13:37,233 --> 00:13:40,236
Were things not going well at work?

258
00:13:41,320 --> 00:13:42,321
Yes.

259
00:13:42,947 --> 00:13:44,031
Or rather…

260
00:13:46,075 --> 00:13:46,951
What is it?

261
00:13:47,535 --> 00:13:48,702
Please tell us.

262
00:13:56,669 --> 00:13:58,045
Look at this.

263
00:13:58,128 --> 00:13:59,088
RESIGNATION LETTER

264
00:13:59,171 --> 00:14:00,965
I got the day before he died.

265
00:14:02,841 --> 00:14:05,135
He said he intended
to quit being a doctor.

266
00:14:06,053 --> 00:14:08,973
Well, I suppose he wasn't suited for it.

267
00:14:19,775 --> 00:14:21,068
Have you heard

268
00:14:21,694 --> 00:14:22,820
from Dr. Honda?

269
00:14:24,697 --> 00:14:25,531
No.

270
00:14:26,448 --> 00:14:27,449
Oh, okay.

271
00:14:37,209 --> 00:14:38,669
Do you know where you are?

272
00:14:39,128 --> 00:14:41,088
- Please.
- Bandages.

273
00:14:41,171 --> 00:14:43,007
I'll take this one.

274
00:14:43,090 --> 00:14:44,133
Thanks.

275
00:14:44,216 --> 00:14:45,676
I'll put some bandages on you.

276
00:14:45,759 --> 00:14:47,219
One, two, three, okay.

277
00:14:52,808 --> 00:14:53,893
Hey.

278
00:14:53,976 --> 00:14:56,687
- Ta-da.
- You little…

279
00:14:59,106 --> 00:15:00,608
- Here, cheers.
- Cheers.

280
00:15:02,818 --> 00:15:04,069
That hits the spot.

281
00:15:06,488 --> 00:15:08,407
You really are something.

282
00:15:08,490 --> 00:15:09,325
What?

283
00:15:09,408 --> 00:15:11,368
Your suturing is so fast.

284
00:15:12,411 --> 00:15:13,662
I guess.

285
00:15:15,080 --> 00:15:18,834
I think I'm better suited
for doing research after all.

286
00:15:23,547 --> 00:15:25,299
I want to be a good doctor.

287
00:15:27,468 --> 00:15:30,804
I listen to the voices of the living.

288
00:15:31,472 --> 00:15:34,850
You listen to the voices of the dead.

289
00:15:38,145 --> 00:15:39,897
Let's both do our best.

290
00:15:41,607 --> 00:15:42,566
Of course.

291
00:16:01,502 --> 00:16:03,212
- Excuse me.
- Yes?

292
00:16:03,295 --> 00:16:05,464
I'm Maki,
I'm getting my car repaired here.

293
00:16:05,547 --> 00:16:07,716
- Police.
- What?

294
00:16:08,550 --> 00:16:11,637
We're investigating an incident
that happened at Miyagawa Park.

295
00:16:11,720 --> 00:16:13,347
Can we talk to you?

296
00:16:13,931 --> 00:16:14,807
Why me?

297
00:16:14,890 --> 00:16:17,643
We're investigating cars that were
in the area that night

298
00:16:17,726 --> 00:16:19,770
and have been brought in for repairs.

299
00:16:19,853 --> 00:16:25,109
GPS records from your company car
show you parked there for 30 minutes.

300
00:16:25,192 --> 00:16:26,402
No, that was--

301
00:16:26,485 --> 00:16:31,365
Your bumper was badly dented, wasn't it?

302
00:16:32,449 --> 00:16:33,492
Let's see.

303
00:16:35,244 --> 00:16:37,121
What did you hit?

304
00:16:37,913 --> 00:16:39,206
I forgot.

305
00:16:40,124 --> 00:16:41,834
One more thing.

306
00:16:50,634 --> 00:16:52,970
So what did you hit?

307
00:16:55,222 --> 00:16:56,682
It turns out

308
00:16:56,765 --> 00:17:02,021
Hirono submitted his resignation
the day before the incident.

309
00:17:02,646 --> 00:17:08,861
It seems he was losing confidence because
his clinical work wasn't going well.

310
00:17:08,944 --> 00:17:11,321
He didn't tell you anything, Dr. Honda?

311
00:17:12,656 --> 00:17:15,784
Well, there are things you can't say
even to friends.

312
00:17:16,660 --> 00:17:17,786
That's right.

313
00:17:18,287 --> 00:17:20,873
He probably couldn't find
the timing to tell you.

314
00:17:20,956 --> 00:17:21,957
I understand that.

315
00:17:24,960 --> 00:17:26,336
Honda, you know--

316
00:17:26,420 --> 00:17:29,423
Don't start with the comforting words.

317
00:17:35,054 --> 00:17:38,515
Well then,
let's re-verify the cause of death.

318
00:17:38,599 --> 00:17:40,684
What does everyone think?

319
00:17:40,768 --> 00:17:44,480
If he was troubled by work,
maybe suicide is possible?

320
00:17:45,064 --> 00:17:47,149
It doesn't look like a suicide.

321
00:17:47,232 --> 00:17:48,192
Right.

322
00:17:51,820 --> 00:17:54,114
Dr. Honda, what do you think?

323
00:17:55,282 --> 00:17:56,325
Um…

324
00:17:59,161 --> 00:18:01,538
Listen, just as an example,

325
00:18:01,622 --> 00:18:06,710
is it possible he fell from a large truck
or a crane by accident?

326
00:18:06,794 --> 00:18:08,170
That might be possible.

327
00:18:08,253 --> 00:18:10,380
But considering the powder residue,

328
00:18:10,464 --> 00:18:13,217
falling from a tree
is also a possibility, I think.

329
00:18:13,300 --> 00:18:15,969
What could those abrasions be?

330
00:18:16,053 --> 00:18:19,681
Did he get caught in something
while he fell?

331
00:18:23,185 --> 00:18:25,854
Yoshimoto,
when will the test results be ready?

332
00:18:25,938 --> 00:18:28,148
They're at the forensic lab right now.

333
00:18:28,232 --> 00:18:29,775
I think they'll be out by noon.

334
00:18:29,858 --> 00:18:31,068
Understood.

335
00:18:31,652 --> 00:18:33,487
Accident, suicide, homicide.

336
00:18:33,570 --> 00:18:35,656
All possibilities remain.

337
00:18:35,739 --> 00:18:39,368
Dr. Honda,
let's go and re-examine the scene.

338
00:18:40,369 --> 00:18:41,578
Is it fun?

339
00:18:44,373 --> 00:18:45,958
Shamelessly digging up facts

340
00:18:46,542 --> 00:18:48,794
and talking about
someone's death like that?

341
00:18:52,506 --> 00:18:55,968
Look, that's not
what everyone's trying to do…

342
00:18:56,051 --> 00:19:00,097
Performing an autopsy, giving findings,
and diligently writing up tedious reports.

343
00:19:01,515 --> 00:19:04,476
That's about all we can do, isn't it?

344
00:19:08,021 --> 00:19:09,022
Let's go.

345
00:19:12,818 --> 00:19:15,070
I have an autopsy report to write.

346
00:19:15,154 --> 00:19:16,780
Take someone else.

347
00:19:18,824 --> 00:19:20,367
An animal jumped out suddenly.

348
00:19:20,450 --> 00:19:22,619
I thought, "Crap, I hit it!"
I panicked.

349
00:19:28,500 --> 00:19:29,918
At the time of the incident,

350
00:19:30,002 --> 00:19:32,296
you were parked there
for a long time. Why?

351
00:19:32,379 --> 00:19:34,715
That was to wipe the blood off the car.

352
00:19:34,798 --> 00:19:36,508
I can't handle blood.

353
00:19:36,592 --> 00:19:39,553
I got a bit lightheaded,
so I was resting with the window open.

354
00:19:41,013 --> 00:19:42,181
Ms. Dojima.

355
00:19:43,432 --> 00:19:45,017
The traffic police informed us

356
00:19:45,100 --> 00:19:48,937
that no brake marks that would indicate
an accident occurred have been found.

357
00:19:55,652 --> 00:19:56,653
Pop!

358
00:19:58,864 --> 00:20:00,157
What are you doing?

359
00:20:00,240 --> 00:20:01,116
Oh, hey.

360
00:20:01,200 --> 00:20:03,869
I tried to contact you
but couldn't get through.

361
00:20:03,952 --> 00:20:05,746
Sorry, I've been busy.

362
00:20:05,829 --> 00:20:10,459
A doctor says a body fell from the sky,
and the crime scene is in total chaos.

363
00:20:11,627 --> 00:20:13,712
Please don't inform my company.

364
00:20:13,795 --> 00:20:14,796
Yeah, all right.

365
00:20:14,880 --> 00:20:16,798
Is he a person of interest?

366
00:20:16,882 --> 00:20:18,634
He hit an animal near the scene.

367
00:20:18,717 --> 00:20:21,720
Did you hear any sounds
like a collision near the scene?

368
00:20:21,803 --> 00:20:22,846
What?

369
00:20:22,930 --> 00:20:24,806
No, nothing in particular.

370
00:20:24,890 --> 00:20:27,059
The interrogation is over.

371
00:20:30,187 --> 00:20:31,688
Hey! What about the sound?

372
00:20:31,772 --> 00:20:32,648
What?

373
00:20:32,731 --> 00:20:34,775
You didn't hear a sound,

374
00:20:34,858 --> 00:20:36,360
but was there anything else?

375
00:20:36,443 --> 00:20:38,403
No, well…

376
00:20:39,029 --> 00:20:40,530
There was kind of a smell.

377
00:20:40,614 --> 00:20:41,907
What kind of smell?

378
00:20:41,990 --> 00:20:42,950
It was like

379
00:20:43,867 --> 00:20:44,993
something rotten.

380
00:21:00,884 --> 00:21:02,302
Why don't you take a break?

381
00:21:04,096 --> 00:21:05,764
Don't bother with that.

382
00:21:07,724 --> 00:21:10,060
Caring for my colleagues
is part of the job.

383
00:21:11,895 --> 00:21:13,981
A very bureaucratic way of thinking.

384
00:21:14,940 --> 00:21:16,233
But I'm fine.

385
00:21:24,574 --> 00:21:25,450
Take this.

386
00:21:27,911 --> 00:21:30,914
They say you need sugar
to make your brain work.

387
00:21:33,583 --> 00:21:35,252
You're quite the meddler.

388
00:21:38,839 --> 00:21:40,007
I suppose so.

389
00:21:41,466 --> 00:21:42,676
Oh, I get it.

390
00:21:43,719 --> 00:21:46,763
It would be a stain on
a bureaucrat's career if someone quit.

391
00:21:48,223 --> 00:21:49,099
Quit?

392
00:21:49,766 --> 00:21:52,060
I can't do this job anymore.

393
00:21:54,187 --> 00:21:55,897
This case made it clear to me.

394
00:21:57,190 --> 00:21:58,191
I just…

395
00:22:00,777 --> 00:22:02,946
can't handle this job.

396
00:22:16,877 --> 00:22:17,919
I also…

397
00:22:20,505 --> 00:22:22,966
did not intend to do this kind of work.

398
00:22:26,303 --> 00:22:28,305
And I'm always hating

399
00:22:29,431 --> 00:22:31,016
how useless I am.

400
00:22:34,311 --> 00:22:36,313
But maybe everyone feels that way.

401
00:22:39,524 --> 00:22:40,942
I wonder how

402
00:22:42,444 --> 00:22:44,112
Hirono felt.

403
00:22:57,084 --> 00:22:58,710
I never thought…

404
00:23:04,216 --> 00:23:06,718
I would never be able to see him again.

405
00:23:10,722 --> 00:23:12,224
If I had known

406
00:23:13,558 --> 00:23:15,018
it would be the last time…

407
00:23:17,437 --> 00:23:19,731
I would have said so many things.

408
00:23:35,497 --> 00:23:37,124
It's not over yet.

409
00:23:40,377 --> 00:23:42,045
You're a forensic pathologist.

410
00:23:58,728 --> 00:24:00,188
Hello, this is Masumi.

411
00:24:00,272 --> 00:24:03,358
This is Yoshimoto.
The results of the lab test are in.

412
00:24:03,441 --> 00:24:04,734
All right.

413
00:24:04,818 --> 00:24:06,194
I'll head back now--

414
00:24:11,992 --> 00:24:13,076
<i>Doctor?</i>

415
00:24:13,618 --> 00:24:15,036
<i>Are you there?</i>

416
00:24:15,120 --> 00:24:16,496
I'll call you back.

417
00:24:28,175 --> 00:24:31,344
No components
matching the powder found on the body

418
00:24:31,428 --> 00:24:35,515
were detected from the trees
or the stadium roof.

419
00:24:36,600 --> 00:24:37,809
Then, Hirono…

420
00:24:38,393 --> 00:24:42,606
It seems like he at least
didn't throw himself from anywhere.

421
00:24:45,525 --> 00:24:49,404
I'm going back to check the test results.

422
00:24:49,487 --> 00:24:53,992
However, a piece to solve the cause of
Hirono's death is still missing.

423
00:24:56,620 --> 00:24:57,996
I never found out

424
00:24:58,663 --> 00:25:00,165
what he was going to tell me.

425
00:25:02,292 --> 00:25:03,376
I'll find it.

426
00:25:07,797 --> 00:25:09,132
All right…

427
00:25:11,259 --> 00:25:13,511
Sorry, did Hirono tell you anything?

428
00:25:13,595 --> 00:25:15,096
Excuse me, I'm busy right now.

429
00:25:15,180 --> 00:25:16,306
Anything will help.

430
00:25:16,389 --> 00:25:18,266
No, I didn't know him well, sorry.

431
00:25:19,059 --> 00:25:20,894
Did anything seem different?

432
00:25:20,977 --> 00:25:22,812
Sorry, I really have no idea.

433
00:25:22,896 --> 00:25:24,606
Excuse me, may I ask you?

434
00:25:26,691 --> 00:25:27,984
Finally, I'm done!

435
00:25:28,068 --> 00:25:29,527
Me too!

436
00:25:29,611 --> 00:25:30,612
Finally.

437
00:25:35,742 --> 00:25:36,868
Shall we all do it?

438
00:25:36,952 --> 00:25:39,496
- Dr. Honda's work.
- Yes.

439
00:25:39,579 --> 00:25:41,539
I guess we have to.

440
00:25:41,623 --> 00:25:42,540
Okay, thank you.

441
00:25:42,624 --> 00:25:43,416
Sure.

442
00:25:43,500 --> 00:25:45,293
Can anyone talk to me?

443
00:25:45,377 --> 00:25:46,962
I didn't know him well, sorry.

444
00:25:47,045 --> 00:25:48,296
I've got work to do.

445
00:25:48,380 --> 00:25:49,381
But…

446
00:25:50,090 --> 00:25:52,342
- Please!
- I'm sorry.

447
00:25:53,635 --> 00:25:55,428
Are you talking about Dr. Hirono?

448
00:25:56,721 --> 00:25:59,182
Where did Dr. Hirono go?

449
00:25:59,266 --> 00:26:01,685
He hasn't fixed my tummy yet.

450
00:26:02,560 --> 00:26:03,395
Well…

451
00:26:04,104 --> 00:26:07,816
Dr. Hirono has gone somewhere far away.

452
00:26:08,692 --> 00:26:11,069
But he gave me a message for you.

453
00:26:11,152 --> 00:26:12,320
A message?

454
00:26:12,404 --> 00:26:13,405
Yes.

455
00:26:14,406 --> 00:26:18,493
He said he's made all the preparations
to fix your tummy perfectly,

456
00:26:19,244 --> 00:26:21,746
so you can just relax
and focus on getting better.

457
00:26:21,830 --> 00:26:22,831
Really?

458
00:26:23,707 --> 00:26:24,499
Yes.

459
00:26:25,125 --> 00:26:26,084
So,

460
00:26:26,876 --> 00:26:27,794
do your best.

461
00:26:30,297 --> 00:26:32,507
Did Dr. Hirono go away

462
00:26:33,800 --> 00:26:35,593
because he made people angry?

463
00:26:38,138 --> 00:26:41,057
A scary man was really angry with him.

464
00:26:42,934 --> 00:26:45,395
He said, "It's your fault she died."

465
00:26:53,862 --> 00:26:55,697
The detailed results are out.

466
00:26:55,780 --> 00:26:58,116
The powder detected on the body

467
00:26:58,199 --> 00:27:01,202
was sodium bicarbonate
containing hydrogen sulfide.

468
00:27:01,286 --> 00:27:05,415
There was also a testimony
about a strange smell at the scene.

469
00:27:05,915 --> 00:27:08,710
It must be putrefactive gas
generated by this.

470
00:27:08,793 --> 00:27:12,547
Could this be why the body
expanded after death?

471
00:27:12,630 --> 00:27:14,674
<i>The gas escaped,</i>

472
00:27:14,758 --> 00:27:16,885
<i>making the body move</i>
<i>as if it were convulsing.</i>

473
00:27:16,968 --> 00:27:18,261
What?

474
00:27:18,345 --> 00:27:20,555
Corpses can move?

475
00:27:20,638 --> 00:27:22,849
It's a special case of post-mortem change.

476
00:27:22,932 --> 00:27:26,436
It's when the body temporarily moves
due to putrefactive gases or rigor mortis.

477
00:27:26,519 --> 00:27:29,439
This also explains
the surrounding blood spatters.

478
00:27:29,522 --> 00:27:33,443
They must have gotten scattered
when he had a violent convulsion.

479
00:27:33,526 --> 00:27:35,445
What happened?

480
00:27:35,528 --> 00:27:38,740
There may still be a piece
we haven't found yet.

481
00:27:44,496 --> 00:27:46,748
Hello, this is Medical Examiner Japan.

482
00:27:48,124 --> 00:27:49,209
It's Dr. Honda.

483
00:27:49,292 --> 00:27:50,335
Got it.

484
00:27:53,546 --> 00:27:54,631
This is Masumi.

485
00:27:55,215 --> 00:27:57,008
I've found a clue.

486
00:27:57,092 --> 00:27:58,510
I think I might know

487
00:27:58,593 --> 00:28:01,805
what job Hirono was talking about
on the night of the incident.

488
00:28:02,889 --> 00:28:03,848
It was…

489
00:28:08,269 --> 00:28:10,688
What did he say?

490
00:28:58,153 --> 00:28:59,404
Dr. Masumi?

491
00:28:59,487 --> 00:29:01,698
The pieces may just

492
00:29:03,032 --> 00:29:04,534
be coming together.

493
00:29:24,429 --> 00:29:27,766
I would like to talk to you
about the incident that occurred

494
00:29:27,849 --> 00:29:29,142
at Miyagawa Park.

495
00:29:32,520 --> 00:29:33,980
Take a seat.

496
00:29:44,240 --> 00:29:45,533
Mr. Takemura.

497
00:29:47,535 --> 00:29:49,412
On the night of the incident,

498
00:29:49,496 --> 00:29:51,247
<i>you testified that you heard</i>

499
00:29:51,331 --> 00:29:54,667
<i>a collision sound</i>
<i>and the sound of a car driving away.</i>

500
00:29:54,751 --> 00:29:55,794
Since then,

501
00:29:56,628 --> 00:29:59,380
no other information has come up.

502
00:30:00,215 --> 00:30:02,091
Not one other person

503
00:30:02,801 --> 00:30:04,761
heard such sounds.

504
00:30:07,013 --> 00:30:08,056
So what?

505
00:30:13,853 --> 00:30:16,022
There were findings on Hirono's body

506
00:30:16,105 --> 00:30:19,484
that looked as though
he had fallen from the sky.

507
00:30:20,735 --> 00:30:21,694
However…

508
00:30:24,322 --> 00:30:28,117
that actually was not the case.

509
00:30:30,954 --> 00:30:33,039
The key to solving the mystery

510
00:30:33,665 --> 00:30:35,917
was the scars on the body.

511
00:30:36,668 --> 00:30:40,255
<i>There were burn-like abrasions</i>
<i>on the right arm and left leg of the body.</i>

512
00:30:41,256 --> 00:30:45,093
There is one hypothesis
that makes these traces possible.

513
00:30:46,761 --> 00:30:50,723
When a person falls in a narrow space
where movement is restricted,

514
00:30:50,807 --> 00:30:56,229
their limbs will rub against the walls
as they fall.

515
00:30:56,312 --> 00:30:57,438
In this case,

516
00:30:58,022 --> 00:30:59,983
<i>near where the victim was found,</i>

517
00:31:00,692 --> 00:31:01,901
<i>in a manhole.</i>

518
00:31:04,237 --> 00:31:09,325
In other words,
the victim did not fall from the sky.

519
00:31:10,285 --> 00:31:13,037
<i>He fell from the ground into the deep,</i>

520
00:31:14,122 --> 00:31:16,124
<i>and died there.</i>

521
00:31:19,127 --> 00:31:22,463
It's natural that no one heard a sound.

522
00:31:23,840 --> 00:31:26,759
The collision sound
echoed inside the manhole,

523
00:31:26,843 --> 00:31:29,387
and no one could hear it.

524
00:31:30,430 --> 00:31:33,808
In his body we detected both
hydrogen sulfide

525
00:31:33,892 --> 00:31:37,770
and sodium bicarbonate,
which is used to neutralize it.

526
00:31:37,854 --> 00:31:43,276
These matched what could be found
inside this sewer.

527
00:31:45,111 --> 00:31:48,531
You're a sewer worker,
aren't you, Mr. Takemura?

528
00:31:48,615 --> 00:31:51,826
<i>We've obtained a warrant earlier</i>

529
00:31:51,910 --> 00:31:57,582
and seized your work equipment from
the vehicle parked near your home.

530
00:31:57,665 --> 00:32:01,169
It's only a matter of time
before we have clear physical evidence.

531
00:32:06,174 --> 00:32:07,467
The person who died

532
00:32:08,426 --> 00:32:10,720
was a surgeon
at Meiwa University Hospital,

533
00:32:11,679 --> 00:32:12,972
Tomoki Hirono.

534
00:32:14,891 --> 00:32:16,434
You know him, don't you?

535
00:32:20,438 --> 00:32:21,856
Six months ago,

536
00:32:23,358 --> 00:32:25,610
your only family member,

537
00:32:25,693 --> 00:32:31,032
your daughter Yumi was transported
to the ER at Meiwa University Hospital.

538
00:32:31,658 --> 00:32:33,034
Yumi! Stay with me!

539
00:32:33,117 --> 00:32:34,827
Don't worry, we'll help you.

540
00:32:34,911 --> 00:32:36,579
Temperature 37.2, blood pressure--

541
00:32:36,663 --> 00:32:38,414
<i>The one who first examined her</i>

542
00:32:38,498 --> 00:32:41,000
<i>was Hirono,</i>
<i>who was still an intern at the time.</i>

543
00:32:42,001 --> 00:32:44,420
The blood tests
show no particular problems.

544
00:32:45,213 --> 00:32:47,256
She may have mild appendicitis,

545
00:32:47,340 --> 00:32:49,801
so we'll have her stay
at the hospital for observation.

546
00:32:51,010 --> 00:32:52,303
Thank you.

547
00:32:56,224 --> 00:32:57,934
<i>But three days later,</i>

548
00:32:58,559 --> 00:33:00,645
<i>Yumi's condition suddenly worsened,</i>

549
00:33:00,728 --> 00:33:02,855
<i>and sadly, she passed away.</i>

550
00:33:04,857 --> 00:33:05,858
Murderer.

551
00:33:05,942 --> 00:33:07,193
You killed her!

552
00:33:07,777 --> 00:33:09,862
Give me… Give me Yumi back!

553
00:33:09,946 --> 00:33:13,366
<i>- You directed your anger at Hirono.</i>
- Hey! Say something!

554
00:33:13,449 --> 00:33:14,993
<i>For a mistake in his diagnosis.</i>

555
00:33:15,576 --> 00:33:17,161
You killed her!

556
00:33:17,245 --> 00:33:19,497
I'm telling you to bring out that intern!

557
00:33:19,580 --> 00:33:20,665
Hurry up!

558
00:33:20,748 --> 00:33:23,126
- What are you doing? Stop.
- Hey!

559
00:33:23,668 --> 00:33:25,878
<i>You went to the hospital</i>
<i>many times after that.</i>

560
00:33:25,962 --> 00:33:27,714
<i>That's medical malpractice, right?</i>

561
00:33:27,797 --> 00:33:30,758
<i>Continuing to claim</i>
<i>there had been a misdiagnosis.</i>

562
00:33:31,843 --> 00:33:32,885
But…

563
00:33:35,430 --> 00:33:38,349
the hospital forbade Hirono
from handling it.

564
00:33:40,476 --> 00:33:42,478
He lost his daughter!

565
00:33:42,562 --> 00:33:44,731
We should apologize with sincerity.

566
00:33:44,814 --> 00:33:48,234
If we apologize publicly,
it means we're admitting a mistake.

567
00:33:49,902 --> 00:33:51,654
I should have urged more strongly

568
00:33:51,738 --> 00:33:55,700
for a retest of the coagulation function
of her blood after the first test.

569
00:33:56,325 --> 00:33:57,910
But isn't the biggest issue

570
00:33:57,994 --> 00:34:01,080
the mistake made in the hemostatic
procedure during surgery?

571
00:34:03,166 --> 00:34:05,334
You won't be able
to become a surgeon either.

572
00:34:09,756 --> 00:34:12,592
You were the one
who performed the initial treatment.

573
00:34:13,342 --> 00:34:15,803
Go ahead, if you want to
give up your future as a doctor.

574
00:34:22,185 --> 00:34:23,102
<i>But</i>

575
00:34:23,644 --> 00:34:25,188
<i>Hirono didn't run away.</i>

576
00:34:33,738 --> 00:34:34,781
<i>He was…</i>

577
00:34:35,656 --> 00:34:37,533
He was trying to expose the hospital

578
00:34:37,617 --> 00:34:42,246
for covering up the medical malpractice
they had committed.

579
00:34:44,290 --> 00:34:46,459
A statement written by Hirono

580
00:34:46,542 --> 00:34:51,005
that explained all of this
was also found in your room.

581
00:34:51,089 --> 00:34:54,133
Does that not mean you knew all of this?

582
00:34:56,636 --> 00:34:57,595
So…

583
00:34:59,222 --> 00:35:00,556
why did you do it?

584
00:35:03,226 --> 00:35:04,852
Why do that to Hirono?

585
00:35:07,772 --> 00:35:08,981
No.

586
00:35:11,359 --> 00:35:12,527
That's not it.

587
00:35:25,289 --> 00:35:27,416
<i>This is Hirono</i>
<i>from Meiwa University Hospital.</i>

588
00:35:28,042 --> 00:35:30,461
<i>Could I talk to you directly?</i>

589
00:35:38,511 --> 00:35:40,680
<i>So now he decides to contact me?</i>

590
00:35:40,763 --> 00:35:44,684
<i>I thought he'd want to settle this</i>
<i>with money, and wanted to refuse.</i>

591
00:35:44,767 --> 00:35:46,602
After the examination is over…

592
00:35:46,686 --> 00:35:48,187
But then…

593
00:35:48,271 --> 00:35:49,564
Let's go for a walk?

594
00:35:49,647 --> 00:35:50,815
- Yes!
- Yes!

595
00:35:50,898 --> 00:35:52,024
Yay!

596
00:35:52,108 --> 00:35:53,151
Nice.

597
00:35:53,234 --> 00:35:55,570
<i>He's the one who killed Yumi,</i>

598
00:35:56,154 --> 00:35:59,615
<i>and yet he's pretending</i>
<i>to be a good doctor, acting so happy!</i>

599
00:35:59,699 --> 00:36:01,951
- Can I have this?
- Sure.

600
00:36:02,034 --> 00:36:03,327
Really? Thanks.

601
00:36:03,411 --> 00:36:04,996
<i>That's why that night…</i>

602
00:36:10,793 --> 00:36:13,171
COME TO MIYAGAWA PARK AT 11:00 P.M.

603
00:36:13,254 --> 00:36:15,089
Sorry, it's work.

604
00:36:35,151 --> 00:36:36,319
Mr. Takemura,

605
00:36:36,944 --> 00:36:38,654
thank you for your time.

606
00:36:40,489 --> 00:36:41,699
No matter how much

607
00:36:42,950 --> 00:36:45,286
I apologize for Yumi,
I can never make amends.

608
00:36:46,078 --> 00:36:49,123
But that's why
I want to take responsibility--

609
00:36:49,207 --> 00:36:50,875
Don't give me that crap.

610
00:36:57,173 --> 00:36:58,841
You killed her.

611
00:37:00,676 --> 00:37:01,802
You…

612
00:37:02,511 --> 00:37:03,638
killed Yumi…

613
00:37:09,518 --> 00:37:11,062
- You're the one…
- I…

614
00:37:11,145 --> 00:37:12,480
As a doctor, I tried to--

615
00:37:12,563 --> 00:37:15,066
- You killed her!
- Please, listen to me!

616
00:37:15,149 --> 00:37:17,485
You killed her!

617
00:37:53,562 --> 00:37:54,855
REPORT OF INTERNAL MISCONDUCT

618
00:37:54,939 --> 00:37:56,440
1. THE FIRST EXAMINATION

619
00:37:56,524 --> 00:37:58,734
TOMOKI HIRONO

620
00:37:59,652 --> 00:38:01,821
<i>By the time I found his report,</i>

621
00:38:02,613 --> 00:38:03,990
<i>it was too late.</i>

622
00:38:29,348 --> 00:38:30,850
Hey. Hey!

623
00:38:47,867 --> 00:38:49,660
But I'm not in the wrong.

624
00:38:50,786 --> 00:38:53,789
His report is proof.
It was all their fault!

625
00:38:53,873 --> 00:38:55,458
Don't give me that!

626
00:38:57,084 --> 00:39:00,463
Hirono was planning to
expose the medical malpractice

627
00:39:01,213 --> 00:39:03,049
and quit being a doctor!

628
00:39:05,301 --> 00:39:07,303
He was taking responsibility.

629
00:39:07,386 --> 00:39:08,429
Dr. Honda.

630
00:39:13,601 --> 00:39:14,810
He…

631
00:39:17,271 --> 00:39:19,607
He was an incredible doctor.

632
00:39:19,690 --> 00:39:21,108
More than anyone.

633
00:39:24,403 --> 00:39:25,529
Why…

634
00:39:27,573 --> 00:39:29,867
Why did he have to have
such a horrible end?

635
00:39:41,879 --> 00:39:46,467
You could say that it was Hirono
who gave us the final clues

636
00:39:47,468 --> 00:39:48,594
to solve the case.

637
00:39:54,642 --> 00:39:57,061
<i>He wiped away</i>
<i>the bloodstains from the murder,</i>

638
00:39:57,144 --> 00:39:59,397
<i>disposed of Hirono's smartphone,</i>

639
00:39:59,980 --> 00:40:03,109
<i>and then it should have been over,</i>
<i>once he hid the body.</i>

640
00:40:06,612 --> 00:40:09,448
<i>But why couldn't he do that?</i>

641
00:40:35,433 --> 00:40:37,143
Post-mortem change.

642
00:40:39,353 --> 00:40:42,440
He glared at me
as if he had come back to life.

643
00:40:45,985 --> 00:40:47,319
And so,

644
00:40:48,529 --> 00:40:49,905
I left him there.

645
00:40:56,620 --> 00:40:58,122
It was for Yumi.

646
00:41:01,750 --> 00:41:03,711
It was all for Yumi.

647
00:41:33,741 --> 00:41:35,743
It's miraculous.

648
00:41:37,995 --> 00:41:41,540
If he had disposed of the body…

649
00:41:45,252 --> 00:41:47,296
the truth might never

650
00:41:49,715 --> 00:41:51,383
have come out.

651
00:41:58,766 --> 00:41:59,725
He…

652
00:42:01,227 --> 00:42:02,686
To the very end…

653
00:42:06,732 --> 00:42:09,276
he was such an amazing guy.

654
00:42:23,249 --> 00:42:26,460
I heard that the medical malpractice
is going to be made public.

655
00:42:26,544 --> 00:42:27,378
Yeah.

656
00:42:27,461 --> 00:42:30,589
Apparently, Ms. Kiryu negotiated for it
at the Ministry.

657
00:42:30,673 --> 00:42:32,675
Wow, I see.

658
00:42:32,758 --> 00:42:34,468
Not bad, for a bureaucrat.

659
00:42:35,427 --> 00:42:36,470
Here.

660
00:42:38,639 --> 00:42:39,723
What?

661
00:42:39,807 --> 00:42:41,100
You did them for us?

662
00:42:41,183 --> 00:42:43,769
No, I was just paying back the favor
from the other day.

663
00:42:43,852 --> 00:42:45,771
You could just say thank you.

664
00:42:45,854 --> 00:42:46,897
Well, it's fine.

665
00:42:46,981 --> 00:42:47,898
Thank you.

666
00:42:47,982 --> 00:42:48,941
Thank you.

667
00:42:49,024 --> 00:42:49,858
Thanks.

668
00:42:49,942 --> 00:42:50,985
Well,

669
00:42:51,610 --> 00:42:52,695
see you.

670
00:42:52,778 --> 00:42:54,363
- Take care.
- Bye.

671
00:42:57,366 --> 00:42:58,909
Oh, good morning.

672
00:42:58,993 --> 00:43:00,327
Good morning.

673
00:43:00,911 --> 00:43:02,037
Good morning.

674
00:43:06,542 --> 00:43:07,585
Um…

675
00:43:12,339 --> 00:43:13,716
Thank you.

676
00:43:49,835 --> 00:43:51,170
I've come to listen

677
00:43:51,795 --> 00:43:53,422
to what you have to say.

678
00:43:56,216 --> 00:43:57,843
I'm a bit late, though.

679
00:44:06,268 --> 00:44:07,936
TNS NEWS ONLINE

680
00:44:08,020 --> 00:44:09,563
4TH CASE OF WOMAN FOUND STRANGLED

681
00:44:15,653 --> 00:44:18,072
SHIRAMINE SERIAL FEMICIDE CASE
RESEARCH DATA

682
00:44:18,155 --> 00:44:20,866
Subtitle translation by: Maslin F.
